revision.text:
{{Refimprove|date=February 2015}} {{Infobox ethnic group |group = Arabs in Greece |image = |poptime = |popplace = [[Athens]], [[Thessaloniki]] |langs = [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Greek language|Greek]] |rels = Majority:[[Christianity]] ([[Orthodox Church]] , [[Maronite Church]], [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Melkite Church]]) ,Minority:[[Islam]] |related = [[Arab people]], [[Arab diaspora]], [[Lebanese people in Greece|Lebanese Greek]], [[Egyptians]], [[Iraqis]], [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]], [[Syrians]], [[Palestinians]], [[Jordanians]] }} '''Arabs in Greece''' ({{lang-gr|Άραβες στην Ελλάδα}}, {{lang-ar|العرب في اليونان}}), known as '''''Araves''''',<ref name="Kniffka1995">{{cite book|author=Hannes Kniffka|title=Elements of culture-contrastive linguistics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j2wbAQAAIAAJ|date=June 1995|publisher=P. Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-2927-4|page=244}}</ref> are the people from [[Arab countries]], particularly [[Lebanon]], [[Syria]], the [[Palestinian Territories]], [[Iraq]], [[Jordan]], many of whom are Christian, and also small groups from [[Egypt]], [[Algeria]], [[Tunisia]], [[Morocco]], [[Libya]] and [[Sudan]], who emigrated from their native nations and currently reside in Greece. Greece has a significant Arab population of about 30,800 people.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}} Mainly from Egypt, Libyans, Iraqis and Lebanon. There are also many Arabs from Syria, Palestine, Jordan, Morocco, Algeria and Tunisia. The majority tend to live in [[Athens]] and [[Thessaloniki]]. However, they can be found in all the parts of the country.
In addition, Greece has people from Arab countries, who have the status of refugees (e.g. [[refugees of the Syrian civil war]]) or illegal immigrants (Algerians of mainly Berber descent and usually mistakenly called Arabs) trying to immigrate to Western Europe.
==Arabs and the Byzantine Empire== In 904, the Arabs sacked Thessaloniki, their greatest achievement in Greece, while four years later they were defeated by Byzantine general Himerios in the Aegean.<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wMGGAAAAIAAJ|year=1965|publisher=Bowes & Bowes|page=65}}</ref> [[Nikephoros Phokas]] noted in 961 the increase of Arabs in Greece.<ref name="Commissionnumismatica1961">{{cite book|author1=International Numismatic Commission|author2=Istituto italiano di numismatica|title=Congresso internazionale di numismatica, Roma, 11-16 settembre 1961: Atti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S0hmAAAAMAAJ|year=1961|publisher=Istituto italiano di numismatica|page=486}}</ref>
