{{blp no footnotes|date=November 2018}} {{Infobox person | image = | name = Nessim David Gaon | imagesize = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1922}} | birth_place = [[Khartoum]], [[Sudan]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = [[financier]], [[commodities trader]] | salary = | networth = | spouse = | children = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Nessim Gaon''' ({{lang-ar|نسيم جاعون}}, {{Citation needed|reason=pronounced NEE-SEEM GAH-OHN|date=June 2016}}) (born 1922, in [[Khartoum]], [[Sudan]]) is a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] financier who created the [[Noga SA]]. Outside the business world, he has been very prominent in Jewish affairs, acting as president of the [[World Sephardi Federation]] since 1971. He has also been a vice president of the [[World Jewish Congress]] and chairman of the board of governors of [[Ben-Gurion University of the Negev]] in [[Israel]].
==Personal life== Gaon was born in the Sudan to Turkish Jews from Spain, who later moved to Egypt and the Sudan. He married to Renée Tamman (1925-2013). He had three children: Marguerite Herzog, David N. Gaon, and Danielle Coën-Gaon.
==Jewish life== Aside from all the posts Gaon has held in world Jewish organizations, he is also a founder, builder and member of [[Hekhal Haness Synagogue]] in Geneva.<ref>{{cite news |first=Amiram |last=Bareket |authorlink= |script-title=he:חשד: בית הכנסת "היכל הנס" בז'נווה הוצת |url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/misc/1.1412435 |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |date=2007-05-25 |language=Hebrew |trans-title=Suspicion: Synagogue 'Miracle Hall' in Geneva was set on fire |accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref>
